n'to members of his cabinet the sub\nstance of the talks he has had in the\nlast few days with the heads of treat\nindustries, like James A. Farrell of the\nUnited States Steel corporation\nThe Information which has come to\nttho president in this way is that the\nlow tide of business depression has\nI been passed and that conditions are\nj beginning to improve in those Indus-\nI jitiies, particularly those which were\nI 'the first to be hit by the buying slump\nand fall In prices.\nj Once the country starts to mend in\nI dustrially, the recovery will be rapid\nNo one is in better position than the\npresident to get first hand information\nas to what big business thinks of the1\nJ .financial and Industrial outlook, and\nIf the captains of Industry see day\nE light ahead, there is reason to look\nI for brighter days.\nH oo\nthe tragedy of\n\"wrong, doing\nDuring the week the papers have\nbeen filled with detailed accounts of\nI the trial of a young woman who was\n\"a rich man's affinity and paramour\nThe story of misdirected lives holds\ninterest because the deepest emo\ntions are touched upon and a girl's\nj fatal mistake is responsible for the\nj fiensation.\nI There is good lo bo obtained from\nthis recital of the improper, disgrace\nI lul relations of a man and young girl.\nand It Is to be in the mandate issued\nlong ago that:\n\"The wages of sin is death.\"\nThe man won the affections of the\ngirl by kind attentions and the be\nstowing of luxuries. But the man, be\nI cause of his dissipations, became at\n1 4imes a brute, and did outrageous\nThlngB. One u i .kness developed an\ni other until tho liner sensibilities dis\nI appeared. The man in his debauches,\nH tried to maim and kill. The scene\nI was closed with a tragedy. The man\n,1 went to a premature grave; the girl Is\njji b nervous wreck, with her good name\nH destroyed and her future blanked.\nThe moral law not only proclaims\nJ tgainst the conduct of this man and\nJ girl, but nature gives its condemna\nH tion. Those who indulge excessively,\nI those who disregard the normal, must\nj pa the cost of their excesses, and\nI generally the first symptoms of the of\nfending is a nervous upset. The man\nIn this case became a nervous wreck, j\nind when his already disordered mind\nI Was Inflamed by drink, he became an\nH Inhuman monster,\nill No one will waste much sympathy\non tho drunken fellow who fell a vie\n\"O Um to him own passions. The girl\nj should have pity. The worid needs\nVil the moral lesson of the fast and false\nUvea which the two led up to the\n:.4 hour of the calamity which over-\nhelmed them.\nH TURNING THE SCREWS\nA ON THE GERMANS.\nm 1 A the days go by. Germany Is dls-\nI j Covering more and more how firmly\n-0 fixed is the determination of the al\nlies to force compliance with the\nterms of reparation.\nj At first there seemed to be a sentl-\n''fM njent in the allied conference in fa\njjjjfl vor of softening the exactions, but\nsnce the further penetration of Ger-\n'lH many by the troops of Great Britain,\n-S3 France and Belgium, the allied leaders\n5'i have shown more firmness and now\nfrlH the demand has been made, requiring\nGermany to pay a billion marks within\nffSSL a week and twenty billion marks by\nH May 1.\n01 it looks as though tho German crisis\nPS la fast approaching, when the Teutons\nfcW' must yield or suffer the further hu-\njnH Bail la tlon of military invasion which\nOUTBURSTS OF EVERET TRUE\nA POMO j JF\nOH, eS, HAvfC THSM (M 1\nTefvJ AKiO FlFTK C6MT gMJgl\nWL 9\" M etC5 cW JA&I jkLJyr\nouR. Pounds\nTHEATRES I\nA, -L.\nThomas Meighan Wins in\nExcellent New\nPicture\nTh showlncr of \"Conrad In ijm-st\nof Youth nt thp Alhambrn theo\ntrr, Inst night, was In th' nature of an\novfction to THorim Uifhani the\nular at't(.r who enthused film fans by\nhis memorablo worl in 'The Mir.nl'\nMan fascinated them a the butler\nSn \"Male and f emale 1 and made ihem\nloe him as the young artist In The\nPrince Chap. 1\nIn thi new William DeMlllp pro\nduction, he portray the role of Con-\nr;ij Warrener, who, having passed\nmiddle ag realizes that he is old. and\nseeks by re-livlng the scenoe of his\nyouth, to make himself young again\nlie finds, ultimately, that tho secret\no' outh Is love and the picture fln\nirhc with a delightful romance.\nThe production is a winner, not\nonlv in theme and plot, but by virtue\nOf the excellent work of the talentel\ncast of favorite, which Includes Ma\nbel \"an Huren, Mnvm Kolao, Bertram\n(ohns, Sylvia Ashton. Kathlyn Wil\nliams. Margaret Lxomls. Charles Cgle,\nftuth Ftenlck and Othen\n\"I he novel, upon which the picture\ni-. founded, is one of Leonard Mer\nrick's most popular stories Olga\nPrlntsclau preserved all the beauty and\ndelicacy of the original story In her\nadaptation The o(her features on the\nlull are a musical stage- attraction\nPatBj and Kathleen O'Connell on harp\nand violin and bltr new two-reel girl\ncomedy, \"Mr. Fatlma\nLove and Thrills Blended\nin Latest Tourneur\nPicture\nMaurice Tourneur's latest Para\nmount production, The Bait,\" will be\nthe feature attraction at the Alham\nbra theater next Sunday and Monda\nHope Hampton, the well known I t\nscreen benuty. plays the leading role\n\"The Bait\" i.- described as a pleas\ning combination of romance, thrills,\nand mystery, with the usual colorful\neventually may carry the battle flags\nof the allies to the streets of Berlin\nand compel all Germany to realize\nmost keenly the sweeping nature of\nthe defeat which was Inflicted in the\nterms of tho armistice.\nFirmness from now on speras to bo\nthe policy of the allied conference and\nGermany Is facing a distressing pe\nriod, if the directing heads of govern\nment in Berlin fail to gracefully ac\ncept the mandates of the allies.\noo\nWITH THE POOR\nOF A BIG CITY.\nSeeking to learn the condition of the\nunemploed In Boston, the mayor of\nthat city spent Wednesday night in\ncognlto at Wayfarers' lodge, where the\ncity shelters the homeless and feeds\nthem in Ihe morning.\nReturning next day to his office, the\nmayor, in tattered and faded hat, ex\nperienced difficulty In gaining en\ntrance, until his secretary recognized\nhim.\nThe mayor was routed out of his mu\nnicipal bed at 5 o'clock In the morn\ning and required to chop wood for four\nhours when he was given his break\nfast of oatmeal, bread and coffee.\nAn experience of this kind might do\nall of us good. In that It should make\nus realize the hardships of poverty\nand the misfortunes of those who aro\ndown and out.\nWhen the misery of the proof is\nnothing more to us than a recital and\nthe actual worry and discomfort Is\nnot felt or understood, we may fall to\ngive that human sympathy which does\nnot fall short of doing our full part in\ntrying to drive back the wolf or hun\nger seen around so many homes at a\ntimo when there Is widespread unem\nployment One or two nights with those who\nare without a dollar and have no re\nsource of any kind to draw on. not\neven friendship, might make us bet\nter men and women in life's general\nactivities.\nTourneur production methods In evi\nden s The story centers around a\npretty Shop girl, who, singled out by\na muster-crook as Mh pawn in u game\nto apiuie and later blackmail a\nyoung millionaire, Is \"framed\" by the\ncrook anil then rescued by him while\non her way to jail. Out of gratitude,\nfho becomes an innocent prey to his\nschemes anil learns the truth onlv\nwhen It seems to be too. late. Hut,\naftiT a thrilling experience, matters\nturn OUt happily\nBesides Mts Hampton, the east of\n\"The Half 'include-. Harry Woodward.\nJack McDonald, Joe Slnjrleton. and\nJames Gordon. John Gilbert wrote the\nj scenario.\nBirthday Program At the\nAlhambra Pleases Large\nAudiences\nThe Alhambra's Birthday Anniver\nsary progiam with Thos. Meighan in\n\"Conrad in Quest of His Youth,\" a de-\nllKhtful comedy, and the Fox e n t s\nwith the i I Councils with harp and\nviolin, who rendered some exquisite\nnumbers which drew hearty applause\nand encores. Tho same program again\ni today, excepting the musical numbers.\nMr Lammer.i will play some popular\nIrish selections on today's bill.\nDangerous Scene is Shown\nin Serial At the\nLyceum\nEileen Sedgwick, daring star of \"The\nDiamond Queen,\" the serial which is\nnow being shown on Friday of each\nweek at the Lyceum theatre. Is an ex\npert motorist Her ability to handle\ntho wheel came her In good stead In\n:the first episode of \"The Diamond\ni Queen.\" Here, racing against death\nin a high-powered car, she sees a child\ndirectly in front of her. while another\nI motor car Is fast approaching from the\nj opposite direction. At the rtsk of her\nI life, to save the child, as well as the\ndriver of the approaching car, the\ni daring driver deliberately turns her\nImachfne into a fence at the side of\nI th road She crashes through it with\nterrific peed. Ml6s Sedgwick staunch-1\nly refused to have a skilled double'\nperform this hazardous stunt. Ex\n'cltement ran high In the company dur\n'tntr the filming of the danger-fraught\nIncident.\n\"Son of Tarzan\" and Bill\nof Unusual Worth At I\nOrpheum Today\nGood things are promised for Or\npheum theatre patrons in the new bill 1\nopening this afternoon. 'The Son of!\nTarzan,\" the wonder Jungle serial, will\nhe seen. After the prel i mlnaries of the\nfirst episode) the second episode today\nwill start to furnish the thrills.\nThe vaudeville program consists of\nsix bright features Including such\niheadliners as the Imperial Grand Op-\nlera quintet, the Mo Moe Japs, a com\npany of clever people from tho land of,\nthe Mikado, with something entirely 1\nI new and novel to offer; Rowland and I\nMeehan, two Shamrocks, with u clever\nact; the Girls of Altitude, a daring\naerial act full of thrills; George and'\nI Ray Perry, man and maid who extract\nsw ot music from a pair of banjos, and\nChase and Iature man and girl with\n1 :'.n extraordinary act.\nSplendid Singing Feature\nIn Presentation of Comic\nOpera \"Ruddigore\"\nwith the Gilbert and BuIUTan genius\nmuch In evidence In the music but\nlacking in the dialogue, \"Ruddlgore\"\nwas presented by the Boston English\nOpera company at the Orpheum the-\natre last night before a rather large!\naudience.\nSplendid sinking wns a feature of\nthe production.\nTheatre goers who love, the whimsi\ncalities of The Mikado\" \"H. M. S\n1 Pinafore,\" \"Pirates of Penzance' and\nthe other famous comic operas of th'\ntwo Englishmen h-(ird and saw much\nin \"Ruddlgore\" which reminded them\nof their favorites, but \"Ruddlgore\"\nseems to lack the movement and laugh\nproducing features of either \"The Mik\nado\" or \"Pinafore.\"\nWhen It comes to music, however.\n\"Ruddigore\" ranks high There are\nall sorts of song. Including those fa\nmous \"Patters and they were well\nsung to splendid accompaniment by an\nenlarged orchestra, which played mu\nsic and not Jazz.\nThere were so many good sonjrs In\nthe production that the music remov\ned tx \"curs\" from much at Hsl 4is\nAMBITION\nI A TRIB1 i i n si PATRICK\n(Bj H, E, SKINNER)\n\nI'd like to serve some worthy causo,\nAccomplish the sublime.\nSomething to load to higher laws\nAnd mark the sands of time.\nI'd like to writ llko Tennyson\nOr rhyme like Pope or Poe.\nI'd like to paint like those who won\nThe praise of Angelo.\nI'd help unfold each day of life\nAnd greet what er0 It sends.\nI d help all rlso above tho strife,\nAnd live as God intends.\nAs patron saint of long ajro.\nSaint Patrick's light still shines.\nTo guide us mortals hero below\nThe way that God defines.\nIDAHO SCHOOL TO\nCHANGE LOCATION\nBOISE, Ida. March 17. Senate,\nbin No, L'98. authorizing removal of,\nthe Albion State Normal school from\nAlbion to Burley. was signed by ,iv\nernor Davis yesterday The bill pro\nvides that tho state board of educa\ntion shall select a site for thi school\nat Rurley. An appropriation suffli I\nent for the moving of equipment, fur\nniture and supplies was carried In the\nbill.\nlogue. There were many chuckles in I\nthe two acts, it is true, but t ho only;\nstrenuous outburst ot mirth followed\nnn American Interpolation In the Brit\nish text. That came when Ihe bad1\nbaronet who had to commit a crime'\neach day confessed that on Tuesday!\nhe had filed a dishonest Income tax\nstatement. The inquisitor replied:\n\"That's nothing; everybody Is loin\nthat.\"\nThe principal roles in the opera were!\nsung by Eugene Loekhart. as Robin\nOakapple; George Rogues as Richard\nDauntless, t he sailor; Bertram Goltru\nas Sir DeSpard Murgatroyd, the wicked\nbaronet,- Marlonnc Godhout as Rose\nMay bud; Alice May Carley, who has .i\nsplendid contralto voice, us Mad Mnr\ngaret, and Eva Qulntard. a clever\ncomedienne, sj Dame Hannah\n!k When 1 make up m Jew'elsJ\nQrQppr' And they shall be mine, 1\n\"fcjT ssith the Lord of hosts, in\nthat day when I makeup\nmy jewels; and I will spare u ern, j\nI as a man spareth his own ron that\nsrrveth him. Malachi VI 7\nf-\nUncle Sam, M. D.\n\nSORE EYELIDS.\nQ. My wlf- hns been troubled with\nsore evellds; the lids swell, almost shut\nand are alwoys r-d nnd Inflamed, and\neach eyelid seems I o he full of pus, and\nthen forms a core which she squeezes\nout. then the eye h-als up till tho next\nmonth, and she- has the rumt trouhlc\nover again We have consulted our fam\nily doctor, and have gone to several spe\ncialists. A Have your wife Iven a ihoroush I\nmedical examination to determine\nwhether there may not be some under\nlying cause for the trouble It may ho\nthat there Is some relation between this\nswelling of the lids and her menstrual\nfunction. I would suggest that you have\nan examination made with a study of\nthis posslhle relationship as one of the\nupeclal points to he Investigated.\nSWEATING OF THE FEET.\nQ. What Is the cause and cure of per\nspiration of the feet? Is there anvtiilr.g\nto kill the odor?\nA. It may be due to poor health, to\nnervousness, to the dlstiirlanen of Cir\nculation due to arch troubles, or ll may\nbe simply a perronal peculiarity. In\nsome ensfs decomposition of the sweat\nLeeds to troublesome odor, not rarely tu\nmuch reddonlnjr nnd Inflammation\nBathing with medicated alcohol and\nwater and the use of talcum or alum\ntalcum powdi-r Rlvo great n-lb f ano .my\ncure. Formaldehyde solutions, more ef\nfective, should not be employed on 'he\nfeel cep-i iimii-r medleei supervision.\nDisinfect the shoes with formaldehyde\nHEART TROUBLE\nQ. Since I had the flu\" my left hand\nfeels as though It were asleep, a numb\nfeeling; left elbow pains at limes. ,ni\nmy shoulder is mid The doctor has told\nme that it Is \"dilation of the heart,' md\nlo- told me not to work so much, put I\nfeel Ju-t as well working. I have a fam\nily of seven, and I do all my own work\nA. You are most Unwise in working\nhard when the physician has told you\nnot to overtax yourself. That is a BUTS\nway to cause the trouble lo continue,\nand perhaps, to get worse In most\nOSjSCS of heart disease, the avoidant S f\nphysical overexertion is of the utmost im\nportance. If you do not follow the doc\ntor s treatment, you cannot hope to get\nwell.\non\nBURGLAR SUSPECTS\nARRESTED IN 3. L.\nSAET LAKE. March 17 In the ar\nrest last night of four men, officers\nbelieve they have broken up a ring of\nburglars which has been responsible\nfor several robberies here ri-cntly. The\nmen taken into custody are James\nHerald, U2; Edward Caples, 3.i; Thom\nas Murphy. li, and Charles Morris,\nWith the arrest of the four men,\nthe sheriff's offu e recovered from\ntheir possession a Buick automobile be\nlonging to Commissioner T. T. Burton,\nstolen several weeks ago.\nPRESIDENT AND PRINCE f\nCHOOSE WILLYS-KNIGHT\n4 Jys\nPRESIDENT HARDING Is 9trong for economy and also is a riignifi.f\ngentleman and naturally likes to travel in comfort and dignity.\nLast fall In choosing a motor car he had more than three hun- W\ndred makes to choose from and after a careful consideration his choice 1\nnaturally fell to the Willys-Knight which is shown m th- above photo.\nThe Willys-Knight is also a very popular car in Europe, the Klna w\".\nof Spam, for Instance, owning twenty of these American-made auto-Hut\nmobiles\nThe Insert in the lower right hand corner show, the Prince of Moi\nWales at the wheel of his Willys Knight roadster, which he likes toVM\ndrive himself. The Prince selected the car while In Amenca on his W.\nvisit last year and took it back with him on the British battleship n\nwhich he toured the world. k-\nWillys Knight cars are sold in Ogden by the Brownmq Autom blleflw\nCompany and an exact duplicate of the car owned by President Hard-1.\nIng is on display in their salesrooms.\nThe largest wooden sectional dry\ndock in the world is on the East River\nfront of Brooklyn, N. Y.\nThe Klffel Tour,- j n pnrs ji still th(\nhighest Btmeftne in the world, it1\n!S4 feet high. 9\n\"A Beauty Sleep\" and then p\nA Beauty Breakfast\" i\nTry it for 30 days to prove St\nThis is what thousands do at the direction of experts to win back the healthful I i\nrose tint to pale cheeks as told by the editor of a famous magazine which is j\nread by half a million women- 'Wyj\n!i 5\nThey take regular exercise, sleep regular hours, and then start breakfast with\nstewed raisins. The raisins are plump, delicious fruit-meats stewed so the juice o A T I \"f!\nforms a luscious sauce. Note recipe printed on this page. A more alluring fruit OtCWeCl XVcUSIUS I\ndish never has been served in any home nor any other food that's more\neffective in this way. 8ok raisins over night, poor water j\noff and place in stewpstn, porting in II\nRead opposite what Eh\". J. H. Kellogg, an authority who has made a life-time's\nnot quite enough water to cover and j\nstudy of foods, thinks of the raisin- You'll serve stewed raisins every morning cook slowly for about an hour, then I\nwhen you know the good they do. Sar to taste and add a bit of vanilla.\nSome raisins do not require- much or v\nLuscious nuggets of food-iron w jj jf